  "prompt": "How do I re-apply for an H1B after cancelled without prejudice?",
  "response": "Re-applying for an H1B visa after it has been canceled without prejudice involves following the standard H1B application process. Here are the steps you should take:\n\n### Step 1: Consult with an Immigration Attorney\nIt's highly recommended to work with an experienced immigration attorney to ensure you follow the correct procedure and to address any specific issues related to your previous application.\n\n### Step 2: Ensure Eligibility\nEnsure that you still meet the eligibility criteria for an H1B visa. This includes having a valid job offer from a U.S. employer for a specialty occupation that requires a bachelor\u2019s degree or higher in a specific field.\n\n### Step 3: Prepare Required Documentation\nGather all necessary documentation, which typically includes:\n- A copy of your passport\n- Educational credentials (degrees, transcripts)\n- Proof of any required licenses\n- Resume or CV\n- Job offer letter from the U.S. employer, detailing the position, salary, and job duties\n- Labor Condition Application (LCA) approved by the U.S. Department of Labor\n\n### Step 4: File a New Labor Condition Application (LCA)\nYour employer will need to file a new LCA with the U.S. Department of Labor. This is a prerequisite for the H1B petition.\n\n### Step 5: Submit the H1B Petition\nYour employer will need to file Form I-129, Petition for a Nonimmigrant Worker, with U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS). Include all supporting documentation and the required filing fee.\n\n### Step 6: Participate in the H1B Lottery (if applicable)\nIf the H1B cap has not been met, your petition will be processed directly. However, if the cap has been reached, your petition will be entered into the H1B lottery. If selected, it will be processed further.\n\n### Step 7: Await USCIS Decision\nAfter submitting the petition, you will need to wait for USCIS to make a decision. Processing times can vary, so be prepared for a wait.\n\n### Step 8: Visa Interview (if outside the U.S.)\nIf you are outside the U.S., and your H1B petition is approved, you will need to schedule a visa interview at a U.S. embassy or consulate. Bring all required documents, including the approved I-797 form, to the interview.\n\n### Step 9: Enter the U.S.\nIf your visa is approved, you can enter the U.S. up to 10 days before your H1B start date.\n\n### Additional Tips:\n- **Address Previous Issues**: If your previous H1B was canceled without prejudice, make sure any issues that led to the cancellation are resolved before re-applying.\n- **Stay Updated**: Keep up with any changes in H1B visa policies or regulations that might affect your application.\n\nBy following these steps and working closely with an immigration attorney, you can increase your chances of a successful H1B re-application.",
